y is pursued and maintained, and where citizens encounter the state in its punitive or monitory roles. Taking a wide view of the period from the 1970s to today, this volume brings together innovative, interdisciplinary case studies of sites of modernity that promise to provide security and safety, yet at the same time are deemed responsible for creating new risks. With a particular contemporary interest in the technocratic changes of security and risk control the contributors to Sites of Modernity — Places of Risk position the 1970s as a turning point in the path from industrial to post-industrial modernity.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aDeutschland. 0aNational securityzGermanyxHistory2DLC. 0aRisk managementzGermanyxHistory2DLC. 0aUmwelt. 0aWirtschaft. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Germany.2bisacsh  aHistory: 20th Century to Present.1 aBecker, Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBuschmann, Maximilian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBöick, Marcus, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGeyer, Martin H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGeyer, Martin H., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHannig, Nicolai, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKrüger, Christine G., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLengwiler, Martin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLindenberger, Thomas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aStanley-Becker, Isaac, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBerghahn Books Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311099770540uhttps://doi.org/